snippet.title: What if India Disappeared? | #aumsum #kids #science #education #children
snippet.description:
What if India Disappeared?
Firstly, if India disappeared, the world famous Taj Mahal will be missed by tourists worldwide.
Secondly, India is the birthplace of yoga, if India disappeared, fitness levels may suddenly drop worldwide.
Thirdly, India is a truly diverse country with over 1650 spoken languages, if India disappeared, this will be a grave loss for humanity.
Fourthly, since time immemorial India has been considered as the land of spirituality, if India disappeared, materialism may become more important.
Fifthly, if India disappeared, world population will suddenly drop as India is the 2nd most populous country in the world.
Sixthly, Indian food is popular world over, if India disappeared, foodies worldwide will be one sad lot.
Lastly, India is a major producer of milk, pulses, rice, wheat, sugarcane etc., if India disappeared, world may face severe food scarcity.

References:
https://fitindia.gov.in/events/unity-in-diversity-of-our-nation-4/
http://www.fao.org/india/fao-in-india/india-at-a-glance/en/

snippet.title: Letter A | Alphabet Song for Kids | Let's Learn About The Alphabet | Phonics Song | Jack Hartmann
snippet.description:
Learn the letter A. This Alphabet song in our Let’s Learn About the Alphabet Series is all about the vowel a.  

Your children will be engaged in singing, listening and following along as they’ll learn to:  identify the alphabet letter, form the upper and lower case letter, say the letter sound clearly and accurately. They will see, hear and say both the long and short vowel sounds at the beginning and middle of a variety of storytelling words.
This letter song also includes a catchy chorus that will motivate your children to want to learn about the alphabet, and at the end, an inspirational reading rap.
All of the alphabet songs in this series have a great beat, lots of repetition and curriculum based reading and language arts content that meets state, national and common core standards.  All of the letters that we use and the way we form the letters follow the Zaner-Bloser Handwriting Manuscript.
Your children will want to sing this catchy, cool, reading skill song over and over.  They will hear the long and short vowel sounds at the beginning and middle of each word.

Listening to this engaging, reading, skill-building alphabet song and following all the printed words and entertaining visuals, your children will develop their phonological awareness, phonics and language arts skills.  
The very helpful educational feature of each song is a close-up of Jack saying each letter sound clearly.  Your children will be able to see how Jack forms his mouth to say the sound correctly.  Children can model these mouth positions so they can say the letter sounds correctly, too.  We hope your children both enjoy and learn from each one of the alphabet songs in our Let’s Learn About the Alphabet Series.  Sing and watch them over and over again.
And, as an extension activity, see if you and your children can think of new words and stories for each letter.  We found searching for words for each letter to be very challenging and really a lot of fun.
